<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   GATT: Investor Trust Recovered Through Reforms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1002182094 Lima Radio Programas del Peru Network in 
Spanish 1800 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1002182094 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima Radio Programas del Peru Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Newspaper of the Airwaves" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Peru has recovered the trust of investors as a 
result of structural reforms, the opening of trade to foreign 
markets, and local competition, within the framework of a 
serious economic stabilization program initiated in 1990, the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade stated today. 
  During an assessment of Peruvian trade policy, GATT 
highlighted the reduction of tariffs in general as a result of 
the government's goal of tariffs reaching 15 percent by January 
1995; the elimination of price controls, subsidies, quantitative 
and exchange rate restrictions; and the policy of state 
intervention. The report states, however, that the private 
sector's reaction to the changes is limited due to the high 
levels of interest rates and taxes, sectoral competition, 
infrastructure deficiencies, overevaluation of the exchange 
rate, and terrorism. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

