<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Superintendency Director on Closure </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1202194494 Lima Global de Television Network in Spanish 
0100 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1202194494 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima Global de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Global TV News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] In a news conference this afternoon, Luis 
Cortavarria Chequeli, director of the Superintendency of Banks 
and Insurance, justified the definitive intervention in the 
Latin American Business Advisory Center [CLAE]. As one of the 
reasons, he mentioned failure to meet the schedule of payments 
to CLAE depositors. 
  [Begin recording] [Cortavarria] Here we have a letter 
stating 
that the clients would begin to get their money on 7 February. 
By this date we had already started to prepare CLAE's closure. 
We reached the conclusion that if CLAE had not started to pay by 
this date, we would start the closure procedure. CLAE failed to 
begin returning the money on 8, 9, or 10 February. I believe the 
superintendent's office made the best possible effort to try to 
formalize CLAE. It is not that we intervened in CLAE even though 
CLAE reported on its operations. CLAE has been handing over 
documents that do not support the reported value of its assets. 
As we said since the beginning, CLAE's obligations to the public 
are not guaranteed. The proper procedure [words indistinct] 
because it is an organization not authorized by the 
superintendent's office. 
  [Unidentified reporter] [Words indistinct] previously? 
  [Cortavarria] What do you mean previously? 
  [Reporter] [Words indistinct] 
  [Cortavarria] Banking Law 637 of 1991 stipulates in a 
temporary article that banks that receive deposits from the 
public without authorization can formalize their status by 
providing information. A process then starts. The law provided 
the opportunity for CLAE to formalize its status, but it failed 
to stick by the law. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

