<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Armed Forces Members of Peace Commission To Be Replaced </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1402161394 Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 11 Feb 
94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PA1402161394 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] It was officially announced that the military 
members of the Peace Commission will be replaced before the 
government begins direct negotiations with the commanders of the 
Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unity (URNG) scheduled for 
early March. 
  Peace Commission President Hector Rosada Granados confirmed 
that Defense Minister General Mario Rene Enriquez Morales 
informed him of his decision to seek new mechanisms to 
participate in the peace process. In that sense, he said that he 
plans to carry out a number of military changes within the 
government Peace Commission. He added that a consensus is being 
sought to determine who will replace Generals Marco Antonio 
Gonzalez Taracena, Victor Manuel Ventura Arellano, and Victor 
Manuel Argueta Villalta. 
  Rosada Granados said he is getting ready for discussions on 
human rights with the URNG and is preparing with information 
from human rights representatives at the Archbishop's Office, 
the Presidential Commission, and Human Rights Ombudsman Jorge 
Mario Garcia, with whom he will arrange a meeting. 
<H5>  Former Guerrilla Commander Offers To Cooperate in Process </H5>
  It was also reported that former guerrilla commander Cesar 
Montes or Macias on various occasions has expressed his 
willingness to cooperate with the peace process, particularly 
with the demobilization of rebel troops. 
  Rosada Granados said that although he has talked with the 
former rebel commander on several occasions, he has never 
expressed his desire to seek amnesty or safe-conduct that would 
enable him to join society. In any event, he added, if he wanted 
to return to legal life, Montes or Macias would be protected by 
the amnesty program implemented in 1986 and 1988. 

</TEXT>

