<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Says U.S. Breaks Immigration Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1502021494 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2321 GMT 14 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1502021494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 14 Feb (NOTIMEX) -- Cuban Foreign Minister 
Roberto Robaina said today the government of President Fidel 
Castro will not make concessions to negotiate with the United 
States, and he accused the United States of not complying with 
the 1984 immigration agreements. 
  "Cuba is willing to talk with the United States but is not 
begging and will dialogue with the United States only on an 
equal footing," Robaina stated this Monday when he called Cuban 
emigrants who are living in the United States and other 
countries to a meeting to be held from 22 to 24 April. 
  The Havana conference, entitled "The Nation and Emigration," 
will attempt to regularize the ties between the Cuban community 
abroad and their relatives and local institutions. The 
organizations that are hostile to the Cuban Government have been 
excluded from this conference. 
  During a news conference, the foreign minister expressed 
regret that contacts to further immigration negotiations with 
Washington have not advanced much, and he said this situation 
"is not due to the Cuban position." 
  According to the Cuban foreign minister, the White House 
"systematically and repeatedly" breaks the immigration agreement 
signed 10 years ago, which mandates the United States will grant 
20,000 visas a year to Cubans who want to travel to that country. 
  An official Cuban memorandum yesterday accused U.S. special 
services and Miami exiles of spreading rumors that visas were 
being granted in order to trigger a massive entry of people to 
the U.S. Embassy in that capital city. 
  Special operations police and Defense of the Revolution 
Committee members cordoned off the diplomatic mission, and more 
than 80 people were arrested in several incidents, official 
sources have revealed. 
  Robaina clarified that the differences between Washington 
and 
Havana and the relations with the community of Cuban exiles "are 
two separate issues" and that they cannot wait to solve the 
first issue to start broaching the second problem. 
  The head of the Cuban foreign office urged the Washington 
government to understand that the Cuban immigrants in the United 
States include a much wider spectrum than the conservative 
National Cuban American Foundation, headed by Jorge Mas Canosa. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

