<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vice President To Meet With Colombia's President Gaviria </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0902161794 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 0440 GMT 9 Feb 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0902161794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 9 Feb (PL) -- Cuban Vice 
President Carlos Lage will meet with Colombian President Cesar 
Gaviria today in the continuation of strengthening bilateral 
ties following the resumption of diplomatic relations a little 
more than three months ago. 
  Lage, who is also secretary of the Council of Ministers 
Executive Committee, will have lunch with Gaviria shortly after 
arriving for an official visit to conclude a tour which included 
Brazil and Venezuela. 
  He will meet with Foreign Trade Minister Juan Manuel Santos, 
who will travel to Havana in the next few days to effect a 
binational commission that was established in the agreements 
signed during Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina's visit 
here in December. 
  He will also hold meetings with Agriculture Minister Jose 
Ocampo, Economic Development Minister Mauricio Cardenas, and 
Health Minister Juan Londono, who visited Havana in January and 
signed cooperation agreements in various aspects of his field as 
well as for the purchase of $7-million worth of vaccines. 
  On the afternoon of 10 February, before leaving Colombia, 
the 
Cuban leader will meet with the board of directors of the Bank 
of the Republic, the central bank which regulates the financial 
and fiscal policy. 
  He will also meet with Armando Montenegro, chief of the 
National Planning Institute, and he will hold contacts with 
various media. 
  Invited by the powerful National Industrialists Association, 
he will hold a working breakfast tomorrow with representatives 
of the industrial sector, associations of exporters, financial 
institutions, and small- and medium-sized industries. 
  The breakfast will also be attended by representatives of 
the 
federations of merchants, cattle ranchers, metal products 
industry, farmers, and the Santa Fe de Bogota Chamber of 
Commerce. 

</TEXT>

