<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ambassador Ayala Appointed UN Human Rights Commissioner </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1502043194 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 14 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1502043194 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The Voz Andes" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The UN General Assembly today confirmed Ecuadoran UN 
Ambassador Jose Ayala Lasso as the first UN high commissioner 
for human rights. His duties will involve the promotion and 
protection of human rights, including the right to development 
and the conception of suggestions to improve its implementation. 
  Upon expressing gratitude for the appointment, Ayala Lasso 
requested the support of all governments and invited them to a 
sincere dialogue. He also pledged to be objective and impartial 
in all situations and with all states. 
  The new high commissioner reaffirmed the universality, 
indivisibility, and interdependence of human rights, although he 
pledged to pay attention to national and regional 
characteristics and to historic, cultural, and religious 
traditions. Ayala Lasso also issued a warning to his own 
country, Ecuador. 
  [Begin Ayala Lasso recording] In the performance of my 
duties, I will be objective and impartial in all situations and 
with all states, but as an irrepressible expression of love for 
my people, which I will soon cease to represent at the United 
Nations, I will be particularly harsh in the execution of my 
duties, to ensure that Ecuador's conduct with regard to respect 
for human rights will be flawless. [end recording] 
  The Ecuadoran diplomat will have the rank of UN assistant 
secretary general. His mandate will last four years as of 28 
February, and he will be based in Geneva. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

