<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   PSD Secretary General Killed; Police Arrest Alleged Killer </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1502234994 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2149 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1502234994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Managua, 15 Feb (ACAN-EFE) -- Today, Tuesday, 
Nicaraguan Police arrested a young man identified as Giovanni 
Alejandro Gonzalez. He is the main suspect in the murder of 
Perfecto Gutierrez, secretary general of the Social Democratic 
Party (PSD), which occurred in Managua last night. According to 
police, the suspect, also known by the nickname "Gasparin," is 
approximately 16 years old and has a criminal record. 
  Up to now, neither the government nor the main political 
parties in the country, including the Sandinists, have condemned 
the murder of Gutierrez, who was 36 years old, married, and had 
three children. The politician, who was also an alternate PSD 
deputy -- one of the seven parties in the National Opposition 
Union -- was hit by two bullets and killed when, while 
accompanied by a young woman, he was parking his vehicle near a 
school in the center of Managua. 
  Nicaraguan Deputy Government Minister Frank Cesar told 
reporters "the crime is being investigated," and advanced the 
theory that "everything seems to indicate" it was a common 
crime. "It seems the reason for the crime was theft," Deputy 
Minister Cesar stated. Cesar also belongs to the PSD, where 
Gutierrez was the secretary general. 
  At noon today, the National Assembly paid posthumous homage 
to the alternate legislator who was murdered last night, and 
demanded that authorities solve the case. Adolfo Jarquin Ortel, 
PSD president and deputy, stated: "We have not dismissed the 
possibility that Gutierrez was murdered for political reasons." 
  Jarquin and Gutierrez assumed the PSD presidency and 
secretary general's positions, respectively, after a PSD 
disciplinary court suspended Guillermo Potoy and Alfredo Cesar, 
respectively, from those posts. 
  Adolfo Jarquin heads the social democrat sector that favors 
constitutional reforms in the parliament. Potoy and Cesar head 
the faction that demands a constituent assembly. These 
differences in the PSD caused a schism between Nicaraguan social 
democrats. Leaflets have even appeared in Managua and other 
Nicaraguan cities recently wherein alleged "recontras" (rearmed 
former contras) accuse Jarquin's sector of being traitors. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

