<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mexico Rejects Army's Offer of Assistance in Chiapas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1502171194 Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 13 Feb 
94 p 67 </F>

<F P=103> PA1502171194 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to a CERIGUA report datelined Mexico City, 
the Mexican newspaper EL DIA has said that the Guatemalan 
Government and Army have played a "dark role" in the Chiapas 
conflict by offering military aid to fight the Zapatist National 
Liberation Army. 
  EL DIA said the Guatemalan Government and Army think 
security 
in the area should be maintained by the two armies, a purpose 
for which the Guatemalan Armed Forces have "offered their help." 
  The Mexican newspaper described the Guatemalan military's 
offer as "unacceptable meddling" and recalled that the Mexican 
Army rejected the offer because it was a local problem that the 
Mexicans themselves would solve. 
  Following the offer of assistance, a joint U.S.-Guatemalan 
military contingent conducted operations under the guise of 
social projects on the border with Mexico, CERIGUA reported. EL 
DIA commented that such operations obscure matters and that "at 
the very least, it can be said that the Guatemalan Government's 
position is openly unfriendly, a stance that should not be 
surprising in view of historical realities," CERIGUA concluded. 
  Army spokesperson Edith Vargas de Marroquin rejected EL 
DIA's 
charges that the Guatemalan Army had offered assistance to fight 
the Zapatists. She added that the Mexican Government and Army 
are capable of solving their sad, delicate problem and have 
requested no help from the Guatemalan Armed Forces. 

</TEXT>

