<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1502201594 </F>
<F P=103> PA1502201594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Guatemalan economic developments monitored through 15 
September. 
  Guatemalan Institute of Tourism Director Jose Miguel Gaitan 
has told reporters that last year 562,000 tourists visited the 
country and spent $265.4 million. Gaitan indicated tourism is 
the country's second best source of foreign currency. (Panama 
City ACAN in Spanish 1834 GMT 9 Feb 94) 
  The government's austerity plan went into effect yesterday 
in 
accordance with Government Agreement 40-94. Consequently, the 
agencies of the executive branch, as well as the decentralized 
and autonomous entities participating in the agreement, must 
implement measures to rationalize public spending. Among the 
provisions contemplated in the aforementioned agreement is a ban 
during the current fiscal year on the purchase of automobiles, 
with the exception of ambulances, patrol cars, and similar 
public services equipment, provided that the corresponding 
budget appropriations have been made. (Guatemala City PRENSA 
LIBRE in Spanish 11 Feb 94 p 115) 
  The Central American Bank of Economic Integration (BCIE) and 
the Banco de la Construccion have signed an agreement to provide 
an additional 5,810,570 quetzals to finance loans for small and 
medium-sized industries within the PAPIC [expansion unknown] 
program. To date, the BCIE has provided a total of 55 million 
quetzales in loans to finance programs for small and 
medium-sized businesses. (Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 
13 Feb 94 p 18) 

</TEXT>

