<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Authorizes GATT Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1502153194 Paris AFP in Spanish 1341 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1502153194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 15 Feb (AFP) -- Peru will join the GATT, it 
was officially reported this Tuesday. A Foreign Ministry 
resolution authorized the Peruvian ambassador to this 
organization to sign the document. 
  According to the National Customs Superintendency, GATT 
membership will not adversely affect the nation's tariff 
collection because there are special provisions for developing 
nations. 
  An expert on the issue noted that initially the application 
of the agreement could generate certain reductions in tariff 
collection, but he clarified that Peru is only obliged to comply 
with the first three of the seven principles set out in the 
agreement. 
  Several days ago, Carmen Higaona, director of the 
Superintendency, expressed her support for joining GATT. 
  GATT members met last week in Geneva, where they analyzed 
Peruvian trade policy and agreed to encourage the Lima 
government to continue its liberalization reforms, highlighting 
its "positive effects." 

</TEXT>

