<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Visit by Peru's Fujimori </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sanctions Against La Cantuta Accused </H4>
<F P=102> PA1602005294 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 2317 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1602005294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 15 Feb (DPA) -- Peruvian 
President Alberto Fujimori said today in Santa Fe de Bogota he 
expects military justice in his country will enforce drastic 
sanctions against those responsible for the disappearance and 
assassination of a professor and nine students at La Cantuta 
University. 
  Fujimori held a news conference at the end of his two-day 
visit to Colombia and said this case "must be fully 
investigated," adding he does not endorse debates on what he 
called "form" issues, for example, the controversy unleashed in 
his country due to the case being turned over to military 
jurisdiction. 
  The president explained Congress issued a law (that allowed 
a 
changing of the venue from a civilian court to a military court) 
which "must be respected." He added the case, considered one of 
the most critical human rights violations in Peru, must be 
investigated to locate the culprits. 
  The disappearance of a university professor and nine 
students 
occurred in mid-1992, when unidentified individuals, presumably 
military, kidnapped the victims. According to journalists' 
investigations, the 10 were tortured and buried in a common 
grave. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

