<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Visit by Peru's Fujimori </TI></H3>
<H4>   Remarks on U.S. Counternarcotics Struggle </H4>
<F P=102> PA1602005494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2335 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1602005494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 15 Feb (EFE) -- Peruvian 
President Alberto Fujimori said in Santa Fe de Bogota today that 
the U.S. counternarcotics struggle has proved useless although 
"billions of dollars were spent." "The change in the U.S. 
counternarcotics policy confirms that this policy did not yield 
the expected results." Although "billions of dollars were 
spent, nothing was attained," he said. 
  Fujimori made the remark in a news conference at the Narino 
Presidential Palace at the end of a two-day official visit. 
Fujimori said that, in view of the failure of the U.S. 
counternarcotics policy, the governments of the coca-producing 
countries, including Peru and Colombia, should outline joint 
strategies and insist that consumption is the reason for the 
persistence of drug trafficking. 
  According to Fujimori, "it is necessary to reassess" the 
alleged reduction in drug use, a crime "that has distorted our 
economies." He insisted that the problem "should be tackled by 
everyone involved" and that "imaginative solutions" should be 
sought. He said the war on drugs as it has been waged, "should 
not continue this way without offering alternatives to coca 
planters." He also said that his country cannot repress "200,000 
poor coca planters" without offering them other ways out. 
  He pointed out that drug trafficking must be attacked by 
"hitting the big ones, not the poor ones." He insisted that 
drug trafficking could end "when there is economic development." 
  The end of drug trafficking, without setting any deadlines, 
"does not depend on us, but on consumers," Fujimori concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32950 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat032_o_94010" </HT>


