<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1502205494 </F>
<F P=103> PA1502205494 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Colombian economic developments through 15 February: 
  Foreign Trade Minister Juan Santos has said the Group of 
Three's (G-3) agreement to create a free trade zone -- the 
Agreement of Economic Cooperation -- has not been stalled by 
tariff issues. According to Santos, the members of the G-3 -- 
Colombia, Venezuela, and Mexico -- fully agree on tariffs, and 
he added that only small details are pending. He also said that 
if everything goes according to plan, the agreement will be 
signed within 30 days. (Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1955 GMT 8 Feb 94) 
  The multinational oil firm Dutch Shell has asked the 
Colombian Government for a 10-year extension of its concession 
for the exploitation of an oil field in the southern department 
of Huila. The oil field, which is scheduled to revert to the 
state on 18 November, yields 18,000 barrels of crude a day. 
Shell said that if the extension is granted, it will comply 
with the terms established by the government and will pay 
corresponding royalties. (Madrid EFE in Spanish 2035 GMT 9 Feb 
94) 
  Official sources said today that Colombia was able to 
increase its banana exports by 10.8 percent during the past year 
despite the difficulties this Latin American export is facing in 
the European market. In 1993, banana exports yielded $400 
million in revenues. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1833 GMT 10 
Feb 94) 
  The expected revenues Colombia will receive from the Cusiana 
oil bonanza have prompted the government to request $400 million 
less in new loans than the planned amount for 1994. This 
measure seeks to avoid a greater increase in international 
reserves, which could interfere with exchange and monetary 
policies. In addition, the government seeks to reduce the 
foreign public debt from $15 billion to $10 billion from now 
until the year 2,000. The Executive Branch has already notified 
the World Bank and the Inter-American Development Bank of the 
move. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 11 Feb 94 pp 1A, 
1B, 3B) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

