<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dominica Trade Minister Prefers Regional Trade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2901021394 Bridgetown CANA in English 1609 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL2901021394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Roseau, Dominica, 28 Jan, CANA -- Dominica's trade 
minister, Charles Maynard, says he is more interested in having 
better Caribbean trade than in boosting trade among the wider 
developing nations. For example, he said, over any "South/South" 
trade, he would welcome an opportunity for "shipping things into 
Barbados." 
  "Let us look at more trade with our neighbours. Let us look 
at more trade in Caricom (the Caribbean Community). Let us look 
at more trade with Guadeloupe and Martinique," Maynard 
suggested. He was reacting to agronomist Arthie Martin's 
suggestion that Caribbean countries should engage in more 
South/South trade. 
  Martin said that traditional trading arrangement which small 
countries like Dominica have with the industrialised world might 
take a beating from international trade arrangements like the 
North American Free Trade Agreement and the General Agreement on 
Tariffs and Trade. 
  Maynard said: "We have engaged in a programme of moving into 
trade with Venezuela... Despite that, this has been on for more 
than a year ... We have not seen any breakthrough." He also 
pointed to trade-related matters with Colombia and other Latin 
American countries, which "have remained merely at the level of 
discussions." He urged local manufacturers here to try to expand 
their exports in and out of the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32964 </DOCNO>
