<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peace Commission Excludes Truth Commission From URNG Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1502225494 Guatemala City Teleonce Television in Spanish 
1900 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1502225494 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City Teleonce Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Telepress" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Peace Commission [Copaz] has decided not to 
include the subject of the Truth Commission with international 
verification in the dialogue with the URNG [Guatemalan National 
Revolutionary Unity] due to resume within the next few days. 
  Copaz President Hector Rosada Granados has explained 
publicly 
the opposition among various sectors within the Army to include 
this topic in the talks; therefore, it will be left pending for 
a future opportunity. Deputy Clodoveo Dominguez, a retired 
military officer, stated this comment this morning. 
  [Begin Domiguez recording] The Truth Commission is a 
commission that, if it were to be formed, should be more within 
the legal framework rather than a political framework. The 
political framework will only serve to stir things up and seek 
confrontation between the various political trends and sectors; 
thus, none of the sectors or the Guatemalan people have anything 
to gain from such a strong confrontation, as was seen in the 
past in Argentina and more recently in El Salvador. 
  If the Truth Commission really serves to heal wounds and 
identify, within the framework of the law, those who in the past 
have harmed the country, then the commission is correct. If 
what is sought instead are ways to reopen wounds and cause the 
Guatemalan people to shed blood again, we must be very careful. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

