<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gaviria Addresses State Council on `Controversy' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1602022394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1602022394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Darcy Queen; from the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] When the country thought the controversy between 
President Cesar Gaviria and the State Council had ended, the 
president sent a letter to the council members, offering them 
his respect. The council members decided to answer with silence 
and to abstain from answering any message. They will wait for 
the results of an investigation being conducted by the Attorney 
General's Office and Congress. This is President Gaviria's 
answer to the State Council: 
  Given the declaration approved by you yesterday I want to 
address, through you, all the council members to reassert, as a 
citizen and president of Colombia, that that high-ranking 
organization deserves my greatest respect; and, by defending the 
government's views in connection with the cooperation given by 
foreign military members in our country, I did not seek to 
insult that important organization. Instead, I wanted to 
clearly state our views on matters that are extremely important 
for the country. 
  I fully share your views, meaning you would rather wait 
until 
a debate is held in Congress to carefully analyze the two sides' 
position. In the end, allow me to tell you I do not consider 
this disparity of viewpoints to be a confrontation between 
branches. Instead, it is a characteristic of a democracy. 

</TEXT>

