<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Costa Rica </F>
<H3> <TI>   Central Bank Report on Foreign Debt Price Rise </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1502214494 </F>
<F P=103> PA1502214494 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The Central Bank of Costa Rica has 
issued a report saying that for the past three years Costa Rica 
has been one the of the "Latin American countries with the 
greatest increases in the price of its foreign debt on the 
international market." In 1990, the face value of the country's 
foreign debt was 30 percent; in 1993 it surpassed 82 percent. 
Between 1991 and 1993 Costa Rica paid $1.525 billion in 
principal and interest on its foreign debt, thereby lowering the 
burden of its foreign debt. Central Bank President Jorge 
Corrales believes this is the result of appropriate 
macroeconomic policies. (San Jose LA NACION in Spanish 1 Feb 94 
p 24A) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

