<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Edenor Investment To Upgrade Networks, Service </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  Buenos Aires LA NAClON in Spanish on 10 January 1994--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> Buenos </F>
<F P=104>  Aires LA NAClON </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] Buenos Aires LA NACION in Spanbish on 10 
January 1994 publishes on page 15 an 800-word report on an 
interview with French economist Philippe Revault d'Allonney by 
Ernesto De Paola and Cristian Mira. The report notes that the 
Northern Electricity Company (Edenor) will invest $100 million 
in 1994 to upgrade networks and service. According to 
d'Allonney, president of Argentine Electricity (EASA), the 
private consortium that took over Edenor, the company will show 
a profit in 1994 if things go as planned. "We knew we would have 
losses in the first two or three years," explains d'Allonney."We 
are very close to breaking even and are certain that we will 
show our first month of profit before the middle of the year." 
The quality of service, he predicts, will "gradually" reach the 
same level as in France. 

</TEXT>

