<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Creation of South American Free Trade Zone Suggested </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1502021094 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
13 Feb 94 p 8 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY1502021094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Silvia de Souza Costa] </F>
  [Text] Brazil is proposing that ALADI [Latin American 
Integration Association] be transformed into a regional 
negotiation forum similar to GATT to promote the creation of a 
South American Free Trade Area [Area de Livre Comercio 
Sul-Americana -- ALCSA]. According to Ambassador Paulo Nogueira 
Batista, the idea, presented by Foreign Minister Celso Amorim on 
11 February during the ALADI meeting in Montevideo, was well 
received by the other 10 countries that are members of the 
organization. 
  "The foreign ministers were very comprehensive and now we 
intend to strengthen contacts so as to prepare a concrete 
proposal as soon as possible. We hope this will be possible 
during the first half of the year in order to begin the free 
trade process on 1 January 1995," Nogueira Batista said. 
  Minister Amorim explained in Montevideo the details of ALCSA 
which was presented by President Itamar Franco to the Rio Group 
at the end of last year. During informal meetings with his 
colleagues, Franco discussed the Brazilian initiative whose 
objective is "to favor economic and social development through 
accelerated free trade" among the South American countries 
within a maximum period of 10 years. The beginning of this 
agreement would be the existing structures of Mercosur and the 
Andean Pact. "We understand that the free trade negotiations 
should be limited to goods and tariffs and nontariffs, through 
which we could simplify and make possible the faster approval of 
these agreements," the foreign minister said. 
  Minister Amorim said that the creation of ALCSA "will 
reinforce the action capability of Latin America in a 
hemispheric and international scope." Ambassador Nogueira 
Batista said that any eventual negotiation with NAFTA (North 
American Free Trade Agreement among the United States, Canada, 
and Mexico) should take place only on a second stage. 
  According to the ambassador, the summit meeting summoned by 
U.S. President Bill Clinton for the second half of the year will 
be political and will not deal with trade matters. An indication 
of the good reception given to the Brazilian proposal was the 
decision of the 11 ALADI members (Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, 
Chile, Ecuador, Mexico, Paraguay, Peru, Venezuela, and Uruguay, 
besides Brazil) to strengthen the association. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

