<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   IMF Receives Preliminary Data on Government Accounts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1102130994 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
10 Feb 94 Business and Finance Section p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY1102130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese and Finance </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia -- During a three-day meeting, the 
Brazilian Government submitted preliminary data on the handling 
of the public accounts during 1994 to the visiting IMF 
delegation. The Finance Ministry is having difficulty accepting 
the 1993 and 1994 accounts of the state governments. 
Additionally, state enterprises are not submitting the results 
of their 1993 activities nor are they submitting their programs 
for 1994. The government does not know the volume of the 
surplus of 1993 accounts that will be disbursed by the Treasury 
in 1994. Jose Cechin, the Finance Ministry deputy secretary for 
economic policy, told the IMF that in 1994 Brazil's public 
accounts will have an operational deficit (excluding monetary 
correction) equivalent to zero. In other words, neither a 
surplus nor a deficit. 
  Jose Fajgenbaun, head of the IMF delegation, who on 10 
February held a brief meeting with Finance Minister Fernando 
Henrique Cardoso, termed the congressional approval of the 
Social Emergency Fund during the first round of voting as "an 
important stage toward attacking the imbalance in the public 
accounts." He emphasized that the government needs to implement 
more measures to maintain the economic plan. 

</TEXT>

