<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Industrial Production Up 9.5 Percent in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94SM0213C Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 18 
Jan 94 p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94SM0213C </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] Industrial production in 1993 will probably prove to 
have risen by 9.5 percent over 1992, its best performance since 
1986. That year, during the consumption boom caused by the 
Cruzado Plan freeze, Brazilian industry grew by 10.5 percent. 
The projection was made by the Brazilian Institute of Geography 
and Statistics (IBGE) on the basis of results obtained for the 
month of November, when production climbed by 2.4 percent. 
  That percentage, which was higher than expected by IBGE's 
experts in the Department of Industry (Deind), means there has 
been a 4.3 percent growth in only two months. To Silvio Sales de 
Oliveira, manager of Deind's Data Analysis Group, the 
explanation may lie in the uncertainty generated by the 
acceleration in the inflation rate, which caused retailers to 
postpone their purchasing decisions until the end of the year. 
It is for the same reason, in his opinion, that December 
production will probably attain at least this same level. 
  What is more complicated to understand is how, in a year 
when 
the inflation rate exceeded 2,500 percent, production rose 
almost as much as under the Cruzado Plan. Here is where two 
important actors come in. The leading role was played by the 
far-reaching adjustment made by industry, which achieved 
significant gains in productivity. Playing a secondary role was 
the surge in demand that started in September 1992, initially 
motivated by uncertainty regarding the behavior of inflation, 
and later by the change in wage policy, which gave workers some 
measure of real gains that were of special benefit to the 
consumer durables industry. 
  From January to November, production of those goods--notably 
automobiles and home appliances), grew by 40 percent, followed 
by capital goods for agriculture (tractors and other inputs), at 
37.4 percent. 
  There are questions about the early months of 1994. Silvio 
Sales believes production may hold up for two months, but with 
some tendency to decelerate. The projection made by the 11 
economists who participate in the qualified information system 
set up by the Regional Council of Economics (Corecon) is that 
January production will be 3.4 percent above that of January 
1993. This would be a modest growth, compared with what happened 
last year. But it all depends, largely, on what happens to 
inflation, and Corecon's projections are that the rate will be 
39.5 percent this month and 39.6 percent in February. 


Brazil: Production Rises 

Industry Segment       Nov 1993/Oct       Nov 1993/Nov       Jan 1993/Nov 
                       1993               1992               1993 

                       (%)                (%)                (%) 

Capital goods          2.1                17.4               14.5 

Agriculture            -5.7               75.4               37.4 

Construction           13.9               -13.0              8.2 

Intermediate goods     2.6                5.1                6.6 

Agriculture and        0.2                10.1               8.8 
livestock 

Construction           3.1                9.2                9.0 

Energy goods           1.0                1.4                1.2 

Consumer goods         2.3                9.2                11.5 

Durables               4.7                38.4               40.0 

Nondurables            1.0                0.8                4.3 

Overall Industry       2.4                8.0                9.6 

Source: IBGE 



</TEXT>

