<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Bolster Protection of U.S. Interests Section </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1302041294 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 0311 GMT 13 Feb 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1302041294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 12 Feb (PL) -- Cuban police have 
supplemented their constant operations of protecting the U.S. 
Interests Section in this capital with additional measures in an 
effort to keep away people who have headed to the office outside 
regular business hours to demand U.S. visas. 
  According to local authorities, this decision was adopted 
because on 10 and 11 February several groups of people -- less 
than 100 in all -- approached the office with the intention of 
entering the office. 
  These people said they heard U.S. radio stations 
broadcasting 
to Cuba report that U.S. visas were going to be issued to 
everyone who wanted to travel to the United States and that the 
protection to diplomatic installations would be lifted [que 
retiraria la proteccion de las instalaciones diplomaticas]. 
  Regarding these rumors, PRENSA LATINA has learned that an 
official of the U.S. Interests Section in Havana has officially 
stated to a Cuban Foreign Ministry representative that such 
reports are completely false. 
  An official communique issued by the diplomatic office today 
said the office will continue to operate normally and that only 
people with previous appointments will be interviewed. 
  The situation around the office was quiet this afternoon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

