<H3> <TI>   Belgian Government Backs Asylum's Request </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1502120294 Brussels BELGA in French 0142 GMT 15 Feb 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1502120294 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed ARS: "Group of Cubans at Residence of </F>
Belgian Ambassador in Havana"; as released by Brussels BELGA 
Database] 
  [Text] Brussels, 15 Feb (BELGA) -- On Monday evening, the 
Foreign Ministry announced that on 26 January last a group of 
eight Cubans, comprising five men, two women, and one child aged 
two years, forced their way into the residence of the Belgian 
ambassador in Havana and immediately sought political asylum. 
  One of the persons concerned has since left the residence of 
his own accord. 
  While awaiting a solution, the ambassador has given his 
permission to the persons involved to remain in the Belgian 
residence, which enjoys diplomatic immunity. 
  In the contacts that were immediately established with the 
Cuban authorities, the Belgian Government firmly insisted that 
the requests of the persons concerned be met, including their 
wish to leave the country. 
  Despite efforts, it appears the Cuban authorities hold only 
a 
faint hope of seeing the interested parties being authorized to 
leave the country directly from the residence. 
  The Belgian Government will, in any event, continue to 
demand 
that a humane solution be found to the situation, including the 
provision of the necessary guarantees regarding the fate of 
those involved in the future. 
  In particular, the Belgian Government will not accept these 
persons being punished for the simple reason that they forced 
their way into the Belgian residence, concluded the press 
release issued by the Foreign Ministry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

