<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Details of Argentine-Chilean Oil Pipeline Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1602160794 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1128 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1602160794 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Neuquen, 16 Feb (NA) -- Argentine President 
Carlos Menem and his Chilean counterpart, Patricio Aylwin, have 
dedicated an oil pipeline of 425 km that will carry oil to 
Chile. This is the most important binational project between the 
two countries. 
  The oil pipeline will increase oil transportation to 120,000 
barrels daily, which will represent $500 million a year of 
Argentine oil exports. 
  Chile hopes to save $25 million through the reduction of oil 
import costs by buying directly from Argentina. 
  The financing of the oil pipeline involved YPF [Government 
Oil Deposits], which provided 57.75 percent of the capital, the 
Bank of Rio with 30 percent, and the Chilean National Petroleum 
Enterprise (Enap) with 12.25 percent. [passage omitted] 
  Argentine Mining Secretary Alejandro Hales said the oil 
pipeline was built in 15 months with an investment of $220 
million, and that "this is a clear example that borders are 
geographical divisions that should not separate but unite." 
  The pipeline will carry from 6,000 to 8,000 cubic meters of 
crude daily in the first stage and eventually will reach 17,000 
cubic meters, about 100,000 barrels daily, that will be refined 
in Chile. 
  YPF President Jose Estenssoro said this "is the largest" 
project built by the two countries and "an important day" for 
the two. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-33037 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat033_n_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-033 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

