<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   PT To Decide on Constitutional Revision Participation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1702131794 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 
16 Feb 94 p A6 </F>

<F P=103> PY1702131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Pomp Column" by Cristina Lobo] </F>
  [Text] After years of shifting (and disputes) among the 
various PT [Workers Party] factions, Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva 
has decided to pay more attention to his election campaign. He 
will attend a meeting of the National Executive and 
congressional party bloc members tomorrow when a final decision 
on the PT participation in the constitutional revision process 
will be made. 
  The results of the meeting are more important even than the 
votes of the PT during the work of the revision process. If 
those attending the meeting approve the proposal to participate, 
it will represent a defeat for the Shiites [fundamentalist PT 
followers], those who do not want the PT involved in broader 
alliances with the center-left, and those who want a radical 
government program. 
  The so-called "flexibility" sought by some PT factions, 
according to their proponents, will permit Lula to increase 
support for his candidacy above the present 30 percent level. 
  The PT candidate is being forced to change his opinion. 
After making a harsh speech against constitutional revision two 
months ago, in accordance with the position of the National 
Executive, Lula now wants a "political participation," which is 
more in accordance with the wishes of the party bloc in Congress. 
  Another meeting with the same agenda took place last week 
but 
results were inconclusive. Lula was touring northern states at 
that time. He could have attended, but preferred not to. Now 
he is being forced to take sides in the PT internal dispute. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

