<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Constitutional Revision Work To Continue Until 15 May </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1602231994 Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network in Portuguese 
2100 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1602231994 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Constitutional revision work will continue until 15 
May. Chamber of Deputies President Inocencio Oliveira said he 
has reached an agreement with rapporteur Nelson Jobim to extend 
the deadline for 15 days. Oliveira wants Congress to vote on 17 
February on a resolution to extend the constitutional amendment 
works -- which are currently scheduled to conclude on 15 March 
-- including amendments to the social emergency fund and a 
reduction of the presidential mandate from five to four years. 
  On 22 February Oliveira will ask the party leaders to 
guarantee the presence of at least 20 percent of their 
congressmen in the plenary hall to guarantee a quorum for all 
constitutional amendment sessions. With the help of political 
parties and the definition of a minimum work agenda, Oliveira 
believes the constitutional amendment works may conclude on 1 
May, leaving 15 days of extra time. He is sure the elections 
will not harm the constitutional amendment process. On the 
contrary, he said, the parties will wait to conclude the 
constitutional reform before defining their campaign strategy. 
  Senate President Humberto Lucena said he will suggest that 
the constitutional revision process be extended until 30 May 
because he said this is the preference of most parties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-33042 </DOCNO>
