<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unofficial Sources Say Bustamante Confirmed Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1702022094 Lima Global de Television Network in Spanish 
0100 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1702022094 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima Global de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Global TV News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Unofficial sources reported today Alfonso Bustamante 
y Bustamante, president of the Council of Ministers, has 
confirmed his decision to resign, which he had made known in his 
resignation letter of 10 February. He has resigned because he 
disagrees with the so-called La Cantuta Law, which has 
transferred the trial to a military court. 
  It has been reported Bustamante confirmed his resignation 
when he learned of the sentences requested today for the people 
responsible for the disappearance of the students and professor. 
  Meanwhile, international agencies reported today 
Bustamante's 
resignation has sparked a new political crisis in the Fujimori 
Government, because the La Cantuta case invalidates all the work 
Bustamante has carried out to improve Peru's image abroad. 
  Bustamante is the fourth president of the Council of 
Ministers of this term. He is also chairman of the Commission 
for the Promotion of Peru's Image Abroad [Comision de Promocion 
de la Imagen de Peru en el Extranjero, Promperu] and industry, 
tourism, and integration minister. 
  Bustamante and Economy Minister Jorge Camet have implemented 
an aggressive economic policy aimed at reestablishing economic 
ties with the developed countries. 
  At the Industry Ministry it has been reported that 
Bustamante 
worked until noon today. 
  The Government Palace has issued no official comment on the 
resignation of the Council of Ministers president. 

</TEXT>

