<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Gomez Endorsement of Pastrana Candidacy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1602230794 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1602230794 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed commentary; from the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Andres Pastrana performed magic. In less than one 
week he succeeded in reeling in Alvaro Gomez and doing away with 
a long- standing split within the Conservative Party. 
Everybody, except for the Alvarists candidates, is happy with 
this. On one side, the Pastrana supporters are happy. With the 
Conservative Party majority assured, Pastrana can devote his 
attention to seeking the votes he needs and consolidate his 
image as a national candidate. 
  The supporters of Liberal Party presidential candidate 
Ernesto Samper are also claim to be happy because they say the 
Gomez endorsement of the New Democratic Force shows Pastrana's 
faithfulness to the old Conservative Party, something that 
weakens his stance as an independent candidate. Pastrana 
supporters respond by saying that what has been confirmed is 
Pastrana's independence regarding his father, Misael. 
  For Andres Pastrana, the challenge is to gather Conservative 
votes and endorsements before and during the party's convention 
on 18 February and continue of appear as the young, independent, 
and suprapartisan candidate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

