<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Accord on Medellin People's Militias Disbanding </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1602185194 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1602185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Juan Ortiz from the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Today the People's Militias and the Valle de Aburra 
independent militias signed a preliminary agreement to disband. 
These are the principal groups of this kind that exist in 
Medellin, Antioquia Department, and control the city's 
northeastern area. They emerged years ago as instruments of 
self-defense against neighborhood violence and extortion by drug 
traffickers' henchmen. 
  The preliminary agreement took effect early today in 
Granizal 
neighborhood, where militias gathered surrounded by a crowd. 
They were transferred under police escort to a detente camp in 
Santa Elena district, 30 minutes from Medellin's downtown. 
  The negotiations began with the reading of the preliminary 
agreement and acknowledgment of this event by Government and 
Interior Minister Fabio Villegas. He described it as courageous 
and as an investment in the future. 
  [Begin recording] [Villegas] This is an example of how they 
can achieve their political goals, how it is possible to strive 
for their ideals amid tolerance, pluralism, and respect for the 
rights and lives of our people. 
  [People's Militias' spokesman Dennis Santamaria] It is 
absurd 
to continue with the armed struggle. We have to think of 
helping the country progress from another perspective, from the 
political and social perspective. [end recording] 
  The preliminary agreement recognizes these militia members 
as 
a political force. They will have six negotiators who must 
remain in the camp and five spokesmen who will mediate with the 
government on conditions for social investment for their 
communities and security in the neighborhoods, the most critical 
issue, since they fear an invasion by the militias of the Simon 
Bolivar National Guerrilla Coordinating Board once they disband 
and become legal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

