<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Cited on Illegal Emigration </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1702022894 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 0100 GMT 17 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1702022894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Evening Information Review" newscast] </F>
  [Text] A spokesman for the Cuban Foreign Ministry 
reiterated that entering embassies is not an acceptable way of 
leaving the country and that those who do so are on the mistaken 
path. 
  In allusion to a group of persons who on 26 January entered 
the Belgian Embassy in Havana, he told PRENSA LATINA that [the 
authorities] will not allow this method to be adopted by those 
intent on leaving Cuba. 
  The Cuban Foreign Relations Ministry spokesman explained 
that 
entering a diplomatic mission cannot be a privilege or safe 
conduct for emigration. In that regard, he said that Cuba has 
not changed its policy and remembered that there are emigration 
laws that allow any citizen to travel abroad, as long as he has 
received a visa and paid for the transportation. 
  The spokesman said that the four men, two women, and one 
minor who are in the Belgian Embassy in this capital must leave 
the diplomatic mission voluntarily and return to their residence 
and undertake the normal steps to leave the country, even if 
they have a visa. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

