<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Rejects Desertion of Armed Forces Soldiers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1802005994 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1633 GMT 16 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1802005994 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 16 Feb (NOTIMEX) -- It was reported here 
today Cuban Defense Minister General Raul Castro had rejected 
the possibility that Revolutionary Armed Forces (FAR) officers 
and soldiers will surrender or desert massively in the future 
  "They cannot dream about massive surrenders or a generalized 
collapse. The fight against us is to the death," the top Cuban 
military commander has said in a speech to commanders, officers, 
and midranking personnel of the western Army. 
  Raul Castro has said the Cuban Government will act 
forcefully 
and coldbloodedly, "will not fall for provocations or allow them 
to take the initiative on any terrain." 
  Raul Castro, who is also the second secretary of the 
governing Communist Party, has inaugurated the annual training 
period of this section of the public force, which encloses the 
western provinces of Pinar del Rio, Havana, Havana City, and the 
special municipality of Isla de la Juventud. 
  He said although the Cuban Armed Forces budget has been cut 
50 percent, the training program for FAR commanders, officers, 
and midranking personnel would be consolidated in 1994. 
  Up to the beginning of this decade, the former Soviet Union 
furnished the Cuban Armed Forces with planes, weapons, and 
ammunition, and top-ranking Cuban officers received military 
training in that country as well. 
  At the event, which was held at the San Antonio de los Banos 
Air Base, President Fidel Castro's brother said despite the 
current economic crisis in Cuba, FAR made "a giant effort" in 
1993 to ensure that its combat capacity not be eroded. 
  He added he had recently visited Army units in the central 
and eastern regions of the island and was able to see how the 
troops were trained, the maintenance given to weapons, the 
preparation of the military operations area, and how the 
soldiers tilled the land. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

