<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Self-Employed in 20 Percent of Authorized Jobs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1802030194 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1800 
GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1802030194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Alfredo Diaz Urbay, director of the Labor Research 
Institute, said that, up until 31 January, a total of 141,637 
people were self-employed. Self-employment is based on Decree 
Law No. 141, which permits the practice of 136 different types 
of jobs. According to Diaz, more that 70 percent of the people 
authorized for self-employment fill less than 20 percent of the 
activities permitted, of which the most common are wagon worker 
[cochero], carpenter, hair dresser, pushcart worker 
[carretonero], and manicurist. 
  As you know, Decree Law No. 141 states that the regulations 
are dictated by two state committees: the State Committee for 
Labor and Social Security, and the State Committee of Finances. 
The first grants permission for self-employment and the second 
deals with collection, since authorized persons must purchase a 
license. This money is income for the state budget. 
  The State Committee of Finances has announced that the 
implementation of an overall tax system is being considered, 
which, if approved, would include people who are self-employed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

