<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Summary of Economic Information </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94CA0061B Santo Domingo EL SIGLO in Spanish 1 Dec 94 p 1-D </F>
<F P=103> 94CA0061B </F>
<F P=104>  Santo Domingo EL SIGLO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Jose Mercedes Feliz] </F>
  [Text] During the first nine months of 1993, government 
revenue increased 14.2 percent over the same period of 1992, 
based on the methodology used by the International Monetary Fund 
(IMF). 
  According to figures from the Central Bank, fiscal receipts 
during the period from January to September of 1993 totaled 
14,493.9 million Dominican pesos. In contrast, during the same 
time frame last year, those same receipts totaled 12,687 million. 
  The 1993 Budget passed by the National Congress for 1993 
totals 22,717.5 million pesos. 
  At the same time, general spending increased during the 
first 
nine months of this year by 39.3 percent, rising from 9,737.8 
million during the same period of 1992 to 13,573.6 million in 
1993. 
  In 1991, revenue totaled some 13,409.9 million, while 
general 
spending totaled 10,340.7 million. 
  At the same time, collections totaled 17,571.8 million in 
1992 and general spending 14,059.2 million. 
  It was observed that from January to September of 1993, 
regular savings totaled 7,943.1 million, an increase of only .7 
percent over the same period of 1992, when the figure was 
7,888.3 million. 
  Regular revenue from January to September of this year 
totaled 14,256.9 million pesos, an increase of 13.8 percent over 
the same period of last year, when the total was 12,527.4 
million. 
  Tax revenue rose by 16.6 percent from January to September 
of 
this year, rising from 11,358.7 million during the same period 
of 1992 to 13,241.6 million in 1993. 
  During the first nine months of this year, income taxes 
totaled 2,493.3 million pesos, an increase of 14 percent over 
1992, when they totaled 2,187.9 million. 
  Likewise, property taxes from January to September of 1993 
totaled 85.5 million, representing an increase of 26.1 percent 
over last year, when the total was 67.8 million. 
  Taxes on goods and services amounted to 5,639.2 million 
during the recent period, an increase of 25.2 percent over the 
same period of last year, when the total was 4,505.6 million. 
  Taxes on foreign trade registered an increase of 8.9 
percent, 
going from 4,550.5 million pesos during the period from January 
to September of 1992 to 4,954.2 million in 1993. 
  Revenue from sources other than taxes dropped 13.1 percent 
during the period from January to September of 1993, going from 
1,168.7 million during the period of January to September of 
1992 to 1,015.3 million in the more recent period, the only 
category recording a drop. 
  Capital income rose by 48.5 percent during the first nine 
months of this year, going from 159.6 million from January to 
September of 1992 to 237 million in 1993. 
  As for the total balance (before deductions) during the 
period from January to September of 1993, the total was 920.3 
million, a drop of 68.8 percent compared with the same period in 
1992, when the figure was 2,949.2 million. 
  Regular savings totaled 7,905.3 million in 1991, 10,545.2 
million in 1992, and 7,943.1 million during the first nine 
months of this year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

