<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cristiani Denies Government Needs Pressuring With Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1802042494 San Salvador Radio Farabundo Marti Network in 
Spanish 1200 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1802042494 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Radio Farabundo Marti Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Early News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Alfredo Cristiani has denied his 
government needs to be pressured into holding free and open 
general elections on 20 March. During his usual Monday news 
conference, Cristiani said he shared the Catholic Church's 
criticism of the political parties' proposals which, so far, 
have been vague and demagogic. 
  [Begin Cristiani recording] I agree with San Salvador 
Archbishopric representatives who say the elections must be open 
and free. I disagree with the alleged need for pressure. I 
believe we all want the elections to be clean, free, honest and 
crystal clear. If something is brewing that could hinder the 
honesty of the elections, it should be disclosed, because I see 
no need for any pressure whatsoever. [end recording] 
  According to Cristiani, the presence of 911 UN observers and 
Supreme Electoral Tribunal delegates will guarantee the honesty 
of the 20 March elections. He also described as unnecessary the 
trip by a Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front [FMLN] 
delegation to UN Headquarters to seek guarantees for the 
fulfillment of the peace agreements. 
  [Begin Cristiani recording] I do not know what the FMLN is 
going to do at the United Nations. Any time they have a problem 
they have to go abroad to level complaints. We are all 
Salvadorans, and there is no need to go abroad to level 
complaints. The rescheduling the FMLN talks about is permanent. 
[sentence as heard] We are trying to fulfill the agreements as 
soon as possible, and to do so we must establish gradually dates 
and deadlines. It is a permanent effort by Onusal [UN Observers 
for El Salvador], the FMLN, and the government. [end recording] 
  Cristiani said among the delayed peace agreements are the 
total deployment of the National Civilian Police, the 
transference of lands, and the reformation of the judicial 
system. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

