<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Political Parties Join Forces </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20384D </F>
<F P=103> 94P20384D </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  [Editorial Report] Managua LA PRENSA in Spanish of 23 
January 1994 on page 3 reports that leaders of the Independent 
Liberal Party for National Unity (PLIUN), the Central American 
Unionist Party (PUCA), and the National Justice Party (PJN) held 
a press conference on 18 January in order to announce that they 
are "joining forces." The parties' communique stated that they 
"...seek alternative viable solutions with a view toward 
Nicaraguans working together to implement these solutions." 
Party leaders invited Nicaraguans to participate in a project 
called "Unity for Change" which offers a "credible and 
trustworthy" program to create "a new political culture." Party 
leaders explained that the country suffers from "a lack of moral 
values, discredited political leaders, and the absence of 
concrete programs to solve its problems." 

</TEXT>

